\end_inset

 be a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\ldots,X_{c}$
\end_inset

 variables over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\ldots,r_{i}$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}\in k[X_{1},\ldots,X_{c}]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F:k^{c}\dashrightarrow\bbP^{r_{1}}\times\cdots\times\bbP^{r_{n}}
\]

\end_inset

be given by the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\underline{x})$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\bbP^{r_{j}}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{0j}(\underline{x}),\ldots,f_{r_{j}j}(\underline{x}))$
\end_inset

.
 In the polynomial ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R=k[X_{1},\ldots,X_{c},s_{1},\ldots,s_{n},Y_{ij}:j=1,\ldots,n,i=0,\ldots,r_{j}]$
\end_inset

 define the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\sum_{j=1}^{n}(Y_{0j}-s_{j}f_{0j}(\underline{X}),\ldots,Y_{r_{j}j}-s_{j}f_{r_{j}j}(\underline{X})).
\]

\end_inset

Then the defining ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[Y_{ij}:i,j]$
\end_inset

 of the closure of the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
