\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\shape italic
Proof:
\shape default
 First, we introduce the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\left(I:\left(\prod_{j=1}^{n}s_{j}(Y_{0j},\ldots,Y_{r_{j}j})\right)^{\infty}\right)\cap k[Y_{ij}:i,j]
\]

\end_inset

and note that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset J$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in J$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in k^{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=F(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Also, there exists a large integer 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\prod_{j=1}^{n}s_{j}(Y_{0j},\ldots,Y_{r_{j}j})\right)^{e}g\subseteq I$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\prod_{j=1}^{n}s_{j}(f_{0j}(p),\ldots,f_{r_{j}j}(p))\right)^{e}g(F(p))=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b=F(p)$
\end_inset

, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

, one of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}(p)$
\end_inset

 is non-zero, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\cdots s_{n}\not=0$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(b)=g(F(p))=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 vanishes on the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, and so on the closure of the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the closure of the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(J)\subset Z(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}(\overline{im(F)})\supset I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k[Y_{ij}:i,j]$
\end_inset

 multihomogeneous if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

, the total 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y_{0j},\ldots,Y_{r_{j}j})$
\end_inset

-degree of all the terms appearing in 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the same.
 Any 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be written as the sum of multihomogeneous polynomials.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in k[Y_{ij}:i,j]$
\end_inset

 vanish on the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Since the codomain is a product of projective spaces, each multihomogeneous
 component of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 also vanishes on the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 If we can prove that each multihomogeneous component of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 So we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is multihomogeneous and vanishes on the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in k^{c}-dom(F)$
\end_inset

, meaning that for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{1,...,n\}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,...,r_{j}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is multihomogeneous, for multi-indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\neq0\in\mathbb{Z}^{n}$
\end_inset

 we have, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\sum_{|\alpha|=d}a_{\alpha}x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 .
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin dom(F)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(f_{j}(x))=\sum_{|\alpha|=d}a_{\alpha}f_{j}(x)^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 must be zero, because each multi-index is not all zero.
 So for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{x}\in k^{c}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\underline{f}_{ij}(\underline{x}))=0$
\end_inset

.
 In short, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\underline{f}_{ij}(\underline{X}))=0$
\end_inset

 (variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 Again by multihomogeneity, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\underline{s_{j}f_{ij}}(\underline{X}))=s_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots s_{n}^{e_{n}}g(\underline{f}_{ij}(\underline{X}))=0$
\end_inset

 for some non-negative integers 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\ldots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots s_{n}^{e_{n}}g\in(Y_{ij}-s_{j}f_{ij}(\underline{X}))$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in J$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the polynomials that vanish on the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and so that the zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 are contained in the zeros of the polynomials that vanish on the image
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, i.e., that the zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 are contained in the closure of the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
